Introduction

Genome-Wide Association Studies (GWAS) are a powerful tool used to identify genetic variants associated with traits of interest across the entire genome. By analyzing the relationship between phenotypic variation and single-nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) in a diverse population, GWAS can pinpoint genomic regions or candidate genes linked to complex traits, such as yield, disease resistance, or nutritional content. This approach does not require prior knowledge of specific genes and is widely used in both plant and animal breeding to accelerate the discovery of markers for use in selection and functional studies.

Background

In the past classes, we presented about the use of QTL mapping in plant breeding. GWAS and QTL have some key differences as follow:

Feature QTL Mapping GWAS
Population Type Biparental populations (e.g., F2, RILs, DH lines) Natural or diverse populations (e.g., landraces, panels)
Genetic Diversity Limited (derived from two parents) High (multiple genetic backgrounds)
Mapping Resolution Low to moderate (due to limited recombination events) High (uses historical recombination in diverse populations)
Allele Number per Locus Typically 2 alleles Multiple alleles possible
Detection Power High for large-effect QTL in controlled backgrounds High for common variants with moderate to large effects
Control of Population Structure Not required (structure is minimal) Required (to reduce false positives due to structure)
Time and Cost Requires population development (time-consuming) Faster (uses existing populations), but may require high-density genotyping
Application Ideal for discovering QTLs in a controlled genetic context Ideal for studying natural variation and breeding populations
Limitations Low genetic diversity; limited to parental alleles Confounded by population structure and rare allele detection

Difference between populations used for GWAS, QTL mapping and genomic selection. Main differences include the number of recombinations and therefore the diversity associated

Historical Background

The historical importance of the age-related macular degeneration, AMD is because before 2005, gene mapping was mostly done through linkage studies. This trait was the first to show that genome-wide could reveal major effect loci in complex diseases â marking the start of the GWAS era.

Information

  • First GWAS example of success is considered the Age-Related Macular Degeneration
  • Klein et al., 2015
  • 116,204 SNPs in 96 cases and 50 Controls
  • Trait: age-related macular degeneration, AMD
  • Very small sample size
  • Polymorphism has a very large effect !
  • Identify 3 significant SNPs
    • SNP2: genotyping error
    • SNP1 and SNP3: intron of Complement Factor H (CFH) gene, a region previously implicated by QTL studies
